name: Ranjit
text:
@Sheel46 @akashblanco Access Point (AP)....  best to use a hard wired CAT 5e connection to the other AP....  Most WiFi routers can be configured to used as AP... but you also get dedicated AP best for business.

If you don't want to use hardwired AP then Mesh WiFi routers are the solution.

name: Ranjit
text: @2ShalabhSaxena Yeah with those many wireless devices.... the ISP supplied routers are the bottle neck or even cheap third party routers for that case start dropping connections.... BTW what's your broadband speed.

name: Ranjit
text: @msomuin Yeah on 30Mbps or even 100 Mbps plans etc it's not a problem but when you start going with higher speed plans like 300 Mbps etc.... and do high speeds transfers often on multiple devices then the bottleneck starts.

name: Ranjit
text: @akashblanco Most WiFi routers even the expensive ones can't properly cover 2 floors properly.... you need to place an AP on the other floor for better coverage.... or invest in mesh network, Trust me I have routers that cost over Rs 30K.

text: @Akshayy_Kumarr @vvrchandra Yeah many of the new inverters have a UPS mode...  Mine is a pretty old one and takes about half a second to resume the the light flickers and that's enough for the router to disconnect.

name: Ranjit
text: BTW a Tip when buying these...  check your Router Voltage and Amp... most would be 12v, 2A or 12v, 1.5A this one supports upto 12v, 3A that's why I ordered as the Airtel Fiber router is 12V and 2.5A.  Generally models supporting higher Amp are more expensive.

name: Ranjit
text: @RAAJ_GunturianN If you already have a UPS and a computer attached then this does not matter, thing is UPS need load and only if a router is attached they disconnect thinking there is no load (auto cut off).

name: Ranjit
text: @vvrchandra I have a inverter but the router disconnects as inverters takes about half a second to power up and in that time, the Fiber router will disconnect from the internet... and these Fiber routers take 2-3 mins to reconnect if disconnected.

name: Ranjit
text:
From a hardware perspective the only thing I miss on the Pixel 4a is the ultrawide camera & other con that I noticed is the ringtone volume is low which is strange as call quality is very loud and crystal clear.

Still enjoying using it as it gets so many basics right.

name: Ranjit
text:
Such a refreshing change instead of the gimmicks & over hyping that's going on in the smartphone world just based on specs... Most  are so un-optimized as brand want to release a new phone every 3-4 months.

It's not the specs but the end user experience & here Pixel4a shines.

name: Ranjit
text:
Using Pixel 4a made me realise you don't have to do fancy stuff to make a good phone. 

Just get the basics right has  excellent call quality, good battery life, excellent tactile buttons & haptic, fast responsive, good camera & stereo speakers.

No gimmicks, just a good phone.

name: Ranjit
text:
@sourapova Dolby digital plus is compressed audio for full Dolby atmos uncompressed you need eARC coz ARC connections simply don't have that much bandwidth for atmos uncompressed audio.

With arc on some models you should be able to get Dolby atoms compressed but differs from model to model

name: Ranjit
text:
@deepkagathara @utsavtechie It depends upon the Soundbar the Sony G700 Atmos soundbar I am testing clearly says in the manual Dolby Atmos is not supported on normal ARC connection it needs eARC connection.

It should technically support compressed Dolby Atmos on arc but it does not so now using it with Xbox

name: Ranjit
text: @deepkagathara @utsavtechie I did that but the Sony Soundbar is not showing ATMOS audio readout when I connected via SAMSUNG arc connection only via XBOX one X got ATMOS on the bar and it definitely sounded much better and different. So its not true ATMOS signal that is being passed if connected via arc.

name: Ranjit
text: @MrAAKASH123 @Chiranj26079099 Later this week or by next week.

name: Ranjit
text: @Chiranj26079099 That's how technology works these are cutting edge new features eventually after 2 odd years these will trickle down to regular TV.

name: Ranjit
text:
@Chiranj26079099 For example the LG GX (2020) model that we have in our office that came for testing has eARC support and some of the new SAMSUNG QLED 2020 models have eARC support.

But my Samsung 65" QLED 2018 model  does not have eARC though its a pretty high end TV.

name: Ranjit
text:
@deepkagathara Its a hit or a miss both the TV and soundbar needs to support for example the Sony soundbar will not pass DOLBY atmos on normal ARC needs eARC support.

But can connect blu-ray play or Xbox with HDMI secon port for atmos pass through but with arc it requires eARC.

name: Ranjit
text: @Chiranj26079099 Obviously they won't even from Samsung and LG only their top of the line models support eARC and HDMI 2.1 for now that do cost couple of lakhs.

name: Ranjit
Ranjit
text:
So my point is if you are buying a high end TV now in 2020, make sure if has eARC support and possible even HDMI 2.1 support for future proofing the same.

Again these features as of now are mostly found only on high end TV's.

name: Ranjit
text:
Getting Dolby Atmos setup is not easy for example for Soundbars HDMI ARC is the way to connect but for Dolby Atmos you need eARC support even on your TV. 

Only latest high end TV from 2019-2020 support eARC so had to use XBOX One X for Dolby Atmos signal to soundbar. https://t.co/BHYGtyBxow
